You’re describing something very close to how a lot of real predictive and planning algorithms work. The key pieces just need to be separated a bit so the mechanism is clear.

1. Yes — expectations come from the past

Any learning system starts with data from the past. From that it builds a model of how things tend to change.

So the model contains patterns like:
	•	when state A happens, state B often follows
	•	certain variables tend to move together
	•	some transitions are smoother or lower-cost than others

This becomes the system’s internal dynamics model.

⸻

2. Prediction is “running the dynamics forward”

Once that model exists, the algorithm can simulate:

current_state → model → possible_future_states

This is forward simulation.

But your description is touching something slightly different: planning.

⸻

3. Planning often works backward from a goal

In many systems, the algorithm does something like what you said:
	1.	Identify a desired future state
	2.	Search backward for a path from that state to the present
	3.	Choose the path with the lowest cost / smoothest transition

This is used in:
	•	robotics path planning
	•	game AI
	•	control theory
	•	navigation systems

A classic example is the A* search algorithm.

Conceptually:

goal_state
   ↑
possible previous states
   ↑
current_state

Then it finds the lowest-cost connection.

⸻

4. The “smoothest connection” idea

Your intuition about “smoothness” maps to something real: optimization.

Algorithms often minimize something like:
	•	energy
	•	distance
	•	time
	•	error
	•	cost

So they look for the path that satisfies constraints with least resistance.

In calculus terms it’s often finding a minimum of a cost function.

⸻

5. Combining both directions

Modern AI systems often combine both:

Forward simulation

present → simulate futures

Backward planning

goal → search backward toward present

When those meet, you get a workable strategy.

⸻

6. Where your intuition is especially accurate

The part you said about:

tracing the connection back as fast as possible

is very close to what algorithms do when they use:
	•	heuristics
	•	gradient descent
	•	dynamic programming

They’re essentially trying to find the fastest path through possibility space.

⸻

7. The deeper pattern

If we simplify it, intelligent systems tend to follow this loop:

past → learn patterns
present → estimate current state
future → simulate possibilities
goal → choose lowest-cost path

That structure appears in:
	•	reinforcement learning
	•	robotics
	•	economic modeling
	•	human decision making

⸻

The key insight in what you said

You noticed that prediction is not magic — it’s pattern reuse plus efficient search through state space.

The system isn’t inventing the future from nothing.
It’s recombining patterns it has already seen, then finding the path that best fits the current state.

That’s a pretty solid intuition about how predictive systems operate.